83
00:05:58,736 --> 00:06:06,163
Next, the act to reduce traffic fatalities and what does this enable the city to do?

84
00:06:10,506 --> 00:06:13,449
Daniel, did you put that on the agenda or whoever added that?

85
00:06:14,690 --> 00:06:15,130
Did you want to?

86
00:06:15,351 --> 00:06:15,531
Yeah.

87
00:06:16,248 --> 00:06:20,451
Yeah, I was the one who originally put this on the agenda.

88
00:06:21,132 --> 00:06:31,040
I should pull up the exact verbiage, but I believe that it does provide the ability for municipalities to set

89
00:06:31,700 --> 00:06:38,182
speed limits, I believe, on specific state roads within their jurisdiction.

90
00:06:39,383 --> 00:06:39,963
I'm not sure.

91
00:06:40,343 --> 00:06:44,624
Amy, can you double check me on that?

92
00:06:44,704 --> 00:06:47,245
I'll go and find the exact verbiage.

93
00:06:50,286 --> 00:06:54,868
Yeah, I believe we still would have to get the approval of

94
00:06:55,753 --> 00:06:59,854
whatever relevant state organization, there's some sort of process for that.

95
00:07:00,494 --> 00:07:10,677
I don't know what that process is yet, or if there might not even be a process yet since the law was just passed, but yeah, we definitely wanna take advantage of whatever we can.

96
00:07:11,517 --> 00:07:14,818
That's changed, so we'll look into that some more.

97
00:07:15,538 --> 00:07:23,260
If we were to reduce the speed limit on a state road, who would have to enforce that in that case?

98
00:07:26,722 --> 00:07:29,284
I'm guessing the state police, right?

99
00:07:29,944 --> 00:07:33,806
Yeah, I mean that all that seems like a kind of a sticking point because they don't.

100
00:07:35,627 --> 00:07:39,790
Necessarily seem, I guess it depends on the the road, right?

101
00:07:39,850 --> 00:07:46,554
Like yeah, we don't see them around a lot of places, but yeah, I just I always I always think that's not there.

102
00:07:46,574 --> 00:07:48,875
That's not really.

103
00:07:50,016 --> 00:07:52,837
But but I think also a lot of people don't know that necessarily, right?

104
00:07:53,398 --> 00:07:54,999
Yeah, so one would hope.

105
00:07:56,432 --> 00:07:56,852
Yeah.

106
00:07:57,393 --> 00:07:58,733
It's one tool in the toolbox, right?

107
00:07:58,813 --> 00:07:59,734
Lowering speed limit.

108
00:07:59,794 --> 00:08:01,195
It's not everything, but it's something.

109
00:08:01,855 --> 00:08:02,075
Yeah.

110
00:08:02,295 --> 00:08:02,975
Yeah, for sure.

111
00:08:04,196 --> 00:08:05,477
Dan, I saw your hand first.

112
00:08:05,737 --> 00:08:06,497
Yeah.

113
00:08:06,857 --> 00:08:17,743
I mean, in general, speed limits are things that people don't tend to pay a lot of attention to except, you know,

114
00:08:18,958 --> 00:08:26,561
as in as much as the road design, you know, affects how fast they feel comfortable going.

115
00:08:26,581 --> 00:08:37,205
So, you know, I don't like there, there might be places where the speed limit is set to an a value that is unsafely high.

116
00:08:37,225 --> 00:08:42,166
And then that would be good to just reduce maybe.

117
00:08:42,386 --> 00:08:45,107
But you know, if there are places where we could

118
00:08:48,041 --> 00:09:09,990
make modifications like i don't know if it's good if it gives us any power to you know suggest modifications to road design on state roads that would then go with a speed limit reduction but like i feel like that would be a lot more effective than just dropping the number well it could be that if that it means that if the if the hope is eventually

119
00:09:11,313 --> 00:09:21,099
When that something on that road will get redesigned, you have a better chance of having that design speed be lower if the speed limit has already been lower for a while.

120
00:09:23,120 --> 00:09:26,962
That, you know, then it's like, well, the speed limit has been 25.

121
00:09:27,643 --> 00:09:33,326
So designing the road for 25 is not a change, whereas if the speed limit's been 35, then.

122
00:09:33,346 --> 00:09:33,506
Right.

123
00:09:37,540 --> 00:09:39,302
Yeah.

124
00:09:39,562 --> 00:09:42,586
And I don't know if that's the way that that works, but it seems like it might.

125
00:09:43,226 --> 00:09:44,648
It could be either way, I guess.

126
00:09:44,708 --> 00:09:48,973
And the question is, like, what do we aim for first, kind of?

127
00:09:49,233 --> 00:09:50,754
Or do we aim for both at the same time?

128
00:09:51,275 --> 00:09:52,617
Or we aim for whatever we can get.

129
00:09:53,037 --> 00:09:53,457
Well, yes.

130
00:09:55,159 --> 00:09:55,420
Bruce?

131
00:09:56,177 --> 00:10:00,658
Yeah, I just wanted to comment both on what B. Dan said.

132
00:10:01,478 --> 00:10:04,999
Regarding how effective it is, you're right, the best would be enforcement.

133
00:10:05,459 --> 00:10:10,600
Hopefully, if it's a state road, the state police would enforce the lower speed limit.

134
00:10:10,640 --> 00:10:23,623
The second is in any sort of crash investigation, a lower speed limit will sway slightly towards not automatically blaming the cyclist because if somebody is traveling 30 miles an hour, for example,

135
00:10:24,323 --> 00:10:29,826
you know, somebody might say, well, you know, the cyclist shouldn't have pulled out or something of that nature.

136
00:10:30,427 --> 00:10:33,989
At 25 miles an hour, there's a little bit more headroom there, for example.

137
00:10:34,990 --> 00:10:41,294
Not that we should expect someone to be honoring the speed limit when you're pulling out in front of them, but nonetheless, there's that liability issue.

138
00:10:41,894 --> 00:10:52,521
And in a civil suit, that could also have impact where, you know, you can show that somebody was violating the law in an incident in which someone needed to collect damages.

139
00:10:53,261 --> 00:10:54,402
So that's what I had about that.

140
00:10:54,503 --> 00:11:03,092
Regarding the original motion here on talking about what we can do with the law, the one thing that I thought was important is the crash reporting.

141
00:11:03,853 --> 00:11:10,961
And that would involve us, I guess, working with the mayor or the police chief or whatever to make sure that

142
00:11:11,922 --> 00:11:27,652
the reporting is done in conjunction and provide a little bit more information about what to look for and what to remember about cyclist operation so that there's not an automatic prejudice by anyone to report that a cyclist was at fault when, in fact,

143
00:11:28,432 --> 00:11:38,680
You know, there were any number of things that the motorists may have done that contributed or with a plain plainly at fault, like passing too close is one example, right?

144
00:11:38,720 --> 00:11:39,580
De facto evidence.

145
00:11:39,620 --> 00:11:43,843
If someone sideswiped you, they were clearly not passing you sufficiently.

146
00:11:44,704 --> 00:11:46,485
And that was previously not law.

147
00:11:48,226 --> 00:11:52,069
Let's see what else I think that's the main thing that I saw red light requirement.

148
00:11:53,738 --> 00:11:59,359
I don't know, it's sort of the common sense thing, where if you're going to be out at night, you ought to be lit, as opposed to just relying on your reflectors.

149
00:12:01,179 --> 00:12:09,561
It does have one thing of interest, which is that you have to have both a front reflector and a rear light.

150
00:12:10,401 --> 00:12:11,541
Oh, right, I'm sorry, I misread that.

151
00:12:11,581 --> 00:12:17,963
An earlier revision required a red reflector and a red light, but I see it's now been changed to only the red light.

152
00:12:18,863 --> 00:12:19,863
All right, so that's it.

153
00:12:22,975 --> 00:12:43,903
It might have an interesting parallel, or I guess that might be an interesting connection to the Medford Bike Lights program that Ernie has been, I mean, maybe there's more opportunity there to get external funding, you know, with this law now being on the books.

154
00:12:46,675 --> 00:12:52,340
or more ways to get attention and get the lights in front of more people who need them too.

155
00:12:55,542 --> 00:12:55,783
Ernie?

156
00:12:57,304 --> 00:13:07,272
Not to talk about bike lights yet, I guess that's the agenda, but just a little bit more data about how speed limits and state cops work.

157
00:13:07,352 --> 00:13:10,815
I remember that speed limits are often set by the 85% mean traffic rule.

158
00:13:14,438 --> 00:13:29,408
to be reasonable and state cops don't want to be pulling people over until it's monetarily meaningful, which by state law is 15 miles an hour over the posted speed.

159
00:13:30,008 --> 00:13:35,052
Then it becomes an unarguable, more expensive speeding fine.

160
00:13:35,912 --> 00:13:43,097
You're not apt to get a state trooper pulling you over for being eight miles an hour over.

161
00:13:43,597 --> 00:13:52,045
whereas you are apt to get an irate Medford or Arlington cop to do that if they aren't busy watching.

162
00:13:52,505 --> 00:13:56,869
I have a speed sign outside my house and I beg to differ on that.

163
00:13:56,949 --> 00:13:57,650
In what regard?

164
00:13:59,451 --> 00:14:02,134
Everybody goes past at 35 or more.

165
00:14:03,655 --> 00:14:05,176
Yeah, I know.

166
00:14:05,357 --> 00:14:07,739
They're clearly not worried about being pulled over in Medford.

167
00:14:10,590 --> 00:14:26,202
But I think that is a good point where if the speed limit goes from, say, 35 to 25 and the state cops are only interested in people going 15 over, now they're pulling people over for going 40 instead of only if they're going 50.

168
00:14:27,684 --> 00:14:36,070
The point is we can't rely on them to do anything except keep egregious speeders from being problematic.

169
00:14:36,451 --> 00:14:36,811
That's all.

170
00:14:37,732 --> 00:14:37,992
Thanks.

171
00:14:39,213 --> 00:14:39,413
Peter?

172
00:14:41,535 --> 00:14:44,357
I'm just kind of going back to what we were talking about.

173
00:14:45,057 --> 00:14:46,999
I can't hear you very well.

174
00:14:47,019 --> 00:14:49,420
Sorry.

175
00:14:50,041 --> 00:14:50,301
Not yet.

176
00:15:08,874 --> 00:15:24,282
Going back to something Bruce was saying about the passing, there is a part of that law as well that actually defines safe passing distance, which is something that Massachusetts hasn't had before, so that might be something to look into.

177
00:15:26,723 --> 00:15:32,126
Because when you talk about passing too close,

178
00:15:33,829 --> 00:15:39,232
That is going to be something because now it's I think three and a half or four feet that you that legally you have to be.

179
00:15:39,252 --> 00:15:42,935
Around a cyclist, four feet down.

180
00:15:43,315 --> 00:15:44,175
Yeah, perfect.

181
00:15:44,436 --> 00:15:44,656
Great.

182
00:15:45,136 --> 00:15:52,661
Yeah, that may be also something that we should make, try to make a lot of noise about.

183
00:15:55,148 --> 00:15:55,549
Yeah.

184
00:15:55,569 --> 00:15:59,130
I think a lot of people have misconceptions about that.

185
00:15:59,370 --> 00:16:09,373
I've heard from a lot of people who were not aware that there wasn't a three-foot rule all along.

186
00:16:11,173 --> 00:16:16,035
I've heard from who are like, I know I'm supposed to give three feet, but they won't let me have three feet.

187
00:16:18,194 --> 00:16:22,659
And, and I sort of start to wonder well where did you even hear that three feet from.

188
00:16:23,900 --> 00:16:32,809
But I think this is, this could be an opportunity for something that would be meaningful for us to put some effort into spreading the word about.

189
00:16:34,062 --> 00:16:37,125
I think there's opportunity for, you know, outreach of various types.

190
00:16:38,106 --> 00:16:40,489
You know, maybe social media, maybe signage.

191
00:16:40,709 --> 00:16:47,556
I don't know if there are any standard, you know, bike passing distance signs that we could put up, Amy.

192
00:16:48,737 --> 00:16:54,303
Not any mass standard ones, but I do know that New Hampshire has standard signs for that.

193
00:16:54,323 --> 00:16:56,546
But I had to look up once.

194
00:16:57,975 --> 00:17:06,017
Yeah, I've seen Florida has a three-foot rule, and I've seen some there that are a little busy, but it's a lot to communicate in one sign.

195
00:17:06,037 --> 00:17:12,078
I always thought an interesting place for that would be an advertisement on the back of a bus.

196
00:17:12,318 --> 00:17:14,818
That might be something that MassSpyke is interested in doing.

197
00:17:15,299 --> 00:17:22,660
We could perhaps inquire or write a letter to them suggesting that they fund some advertising in that regard.

198
00:17:22,680 --> 00:17:26,801
It seems like that would be a very effective way of advertising

199
00:17:27,711 --> 00:17:28,512
a three-foot rule.

200
00:17:29,453 --> 00:17:36,861
I've always wondered why bike organizations like MassBike didn't put PSAs on the backs of buses all the time.

201
00:17:36,881 --> 00:17:38,783
It's probably expensive.

202
00:17:39,103 --> 00:17:40,024
I'm sure it's expensive.

203
00:17:40,064 --> 00:17:43,408
It's probably not so expensive that it's not feasible once in a while.

204
00:17:44,585 --> 00:17:59,468
In Canada, I picked up a nice metallic rear bumper sticker, very well made, showing a bicyclist in a car going by with double arrow and a one meter, one M. So it's clear that they've gone metric on that.

205
00:17:59,508 --> 00:18:05,990
Does anyone know if there's that kind of standard in the EU or at least outside of North America?

206
00:18:06,950 --> 00:18:09,152
where metric has taken over.

207
00:18:09,312 --> 00:18:12,274
Because four feet is what, 1.2 meters?

208
00:18:12,414 --> 00:18:12,935
It's weird.

209
00:18:14,036 --> 00:18:18,139
I don't think we have to worry about people wanting to use metric in the US.

210
00:18:18,599 --> 00:18:21,541
I think we can use four feet and people will understand what four feet is here.

211
00:18:22,442 --> 00:18:24,624
That's the unfortunate part about it.

212
00:18:24,684 --> 00:18:28,306
I was just curious as to what's standardized now in the EU.

213
00:18:28,827 --> 00:18:31,369
I suspect it might still be one meter, but I don't know.

214
00:18:31,829 --> 00:18:32,590
It might be.

215
00:18:33,550 --> 00:18:35,071
I know that when I was in Germany,

216
00:18:36,136 --> 00:18:38,717
close passing was just not a thing that I thought about.

217
00:18:38,737 --> 00:18:43,639
It was like people just didn't do it.

218
00:18:43,659 --> 00:18:50,983
I don't know if they were thinking, oh, it has to be at least a meter, but I think more often it was

219
00:18:52,443 --> 00:18:54,604
you make a lane change, you cross the center line.

220
00:18:54,664 --> 00:18:57,664
So you go, if you have to cross the center line, you cross it all the way.

221
00:18:57,684 --> 00:19:01,625
Um, and if you don't have room to do that, then you don't pass until you do.

222
00:19:01,645 --> 00:19:07,087
So, so in, in that, that's, and that was more of like what people actually did.

223
